The numbers of Afghans returning to their country have increased following the Taliban's takeover in 2021. Pakistan has also introduced new visa requirements for residents in the border town of Chaman, leading to protests and disruptions.
articles.title: Over 4 lakh Afghans return home from Pak following crackdown

articles.description: Foreigners, including UN agency staff, are being evacuated from Myanmar as an insurgency against military rule intensifies. Ethnic minority insurgents allied with a pro-democracy civilian government launched an offensive last month, trapping hundreds of foreigners in conflict areas. China is assisting in the evacuation of its nationals and other foreigners. The civilian government-in-exile said that anti-junta forces in Kayah State had temporarily paused their offensive to allow aid workers to leave.
articles.title: Foreigners, aid workers moved to safety from Myanmar fighting

articles.description: A wooden boat carrying Rohingya refugees was denied entry into western Indonesia by local communities, despite pleas from the desperate men onboard. Over 800 Rohingya refugees have arrived in Indonesia's Aceh province in the past week. While sympathies exist among Acehnese locals, concerns over resources, conflicts, and smuggling networks have caused tensions. The refugees who were eventually allowed to land still face an uncertain future in Aceh, as locals may force them back to sea. Indonesia, not being a signatory of the UN Refugee Convention, is not compelled to accept Rohingya refugees.
articles.title: Rohingya refugees not welcome in Indonesia

articles.description: US Secretary of Defense Lloyd Austin visited Kyiv to show unwavering support for Ukraine in its fight against Russia's aggression. The visit comes amid concerns about the sustainability of Western assistance as the war with Russia continues. The US ambassador to Kyiv, Bridget Brink, emphasized the visit's significance in demonstrating Washington's support for Ukraine's fight for freedom. The trip also coincides with increasing division in the US legislature over aid for Ukraine, with a joint military industry conference between Ukraine and the US planned for next month.
articles.title: US's Austin visits wartime Kyiv in gesture of support for Ukraine

articles.description: An accountability court in Islamabad has ordered Pakistan's anti-graft body to record the statement of former Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif by November 30 in the Toshakhana corruption case. Sharif's lawyer requested the court to direct the National Accountability Bureau (NAB) to record his client's statements. Sharif, along with former President Asif Ali Zardari and ex-Prime Minister Yousuf Raza Gilani, is accused of illegally retaining vehicles gifted by foreign countries.
articles.title: Pakistan's anti-graft body ordered to record ex-PM Nawaz Sharif's statement by Nov 30

articles.description: Today marks the 25th anniversary of the International Space Station (ISS), symbolizing international collaboration in space exploration. With contributions from multiple countries, the ISS has played a crucial role in advancing our understanding of space and microgravity through scientific research. It has also served as a testbed for studying the effects of long-duration space missions on the human body, providing valuable knowledge for future endeavors.
articles.title: Today in history: International Space Station turns 25

articles.description: The Drug Regulatory Authority of Pakistan (DRAP) has issued a public warning about batch L-083 of Weena Syrup, produced by Ms Swat Pharmaceuticals. The syrup is commonly used to treat iron deficiency anemia. The defective batch can cause gastrointestinal distress symptoms. Citizens are advised not to use this batch, and the manufacturer has been directed to recall it from the market. Pharmacies have been instructed to stop supplying the batch and return any remaining stock. The Punjab government has also recently banned five cough syrups due to excessive amounts of alcohol.
articles.title: Pakistan: Warning issued against batch of widely-consumed syrup; recall initiated due to potential health risks

articles.author: Chidanand Rajghatta
articles.description: The tech world was convulsed on Friday after the board of directors of OpenAI, whose investors include Microsoft and Infosys, ousted CEO Sam Altman, saying it had lost confidence in his ability to lead the artificial intelligence pioneer and that “he was not consistently candid in his communications with the board”. Mira Murati, previously OpenAI’s chief technology officer, has been named interim CEO of the company that introduced to the world the popular chatbot ChatGPT.
articles.title: OpenAI fires co-founder Sam Altman on video call, convulsing tech world

articles.description: UK Treasury chief Jeremy Hunt has stated that the government can lower taxes as inflation falls, but this will be accompanied by cuts to welfare benefits. Hunt's autumn budget statement is expected to provide relief for businesses and wealthy property owners. He emphasized the need for difficult decisions to reform the welfare state and get more people back to work. Critics argue that cutting inheritance tax may leave poorer people vulnerable, considering the country's economic state. The Conservatives are trailing behind the Labour Party in opinion polls ahead of the national election.
articles.title: UK Treasury chief signals tax cuts, squeeze on welfare benefits on way

articles.description: US President Joe Biden's Middle East adviser, Brett McGurk, has stated that there will be a "significant pause" in the Israel-Hamas war if hostages held in Gaza are freed. McGurk emphasized that the release of hostages would result in a surge of humanitarian relief. Efforts by Qatar have led to the release of four captives so far, with hopes of freeing the remaining hostages. Israel has refused to agree to a ceasefire until all hostages are released.
articles.title: No 'significant' pause in Gaza war before hostage releases: US official

articles.description: Argentine presidential candidate Javier Milei caused a commotion when he attended a production of Madame Butterfly at Buenos Aires' Teatro Colon. Milei, known for his radical libertarian views and promises to cut government spending, faced heckling from opponents and applause from supporters. The incident highlights the polarizing nature of the upcoming election, with Milei running against center-left Economy Minister Sergio Massa. The incident has gained widespread attention on social media.
articles.title: Argentina's Javier Milei gets mixed reception during night at the opera

articles.description: The construction of a new freight train line in northern Mexico is threatening the biodiversity and habitats of various animal species. The project, which has been shrouded in secrecy, has raised concerns among local residents and conservationists who claim it ignores environmental considerations. The new rail line will fragment habitats. The lack of official information and communication from authorities has made it difficult for locals to understand the purpose and impact of the project.
articles.title: Residents battling a new train line in northern Mexico face a wall of government secrecy

articles.description: Javier Milei, a right-wing Argentine presidential candidate, is following Donald Trump's playbook by claiming that election results are dubious and that he may be deprived of the nation's top job. Analysts believe this tactic is meant to energize Milei's base and promote vigilance at polling stations, or to set the stage for refusing to concede a loss. While Argentina's voting system has some irregularities, it is unlikely that fraud on a scale to sway an election could occur.
articles.title: Javier Milei echoes DonaldTrump with fraud claims that inject uncertainty into Argentina's presidential runoff

articles.description: Thousands of family members and supporters of hostages held in Gaza marched in Jerusalem, criticizing Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's handling of the war with Hamas. The protesters pleaded with the government to do more to bring their loved ones home. The march marked the culmination of a five-day trek from Tel Aviv and represented the largest protest on behalf of the hostages since they were taken by Hamas on October 7. Israeli leaders have set two objectives.
articles.title: In march on Jerusalem, thousands press Israeli government to do more to free hostages held in Gaza

articles.description: A Brazilian fan of Taylor Swift died after falling ill at the singer's concert in Rio de Janeiro. The government has ordered that drinking water be provided and easily accessible at future shows. The cause of the fan's death is unknown and will be investigated. Swift expressed her condolences to the fan's family and friends. The intense heat at the concert led to several fans falling ill, prompting Swift to interrupt her performance and request water for them.
articles.title: Taylor Swift fan dies at show in sweltering Rio de Janeiro

articles.description: The United Arab Emirates (UAE) has received the first group of Palestinian children wounded in the ongoing Israel-Hamas war in Gaza. The UAE has pledged to aid 1,000 children and the group of 15 people, including children and their family members, made it to Abu Dhabi after crossing the Rafah border with Egypt. Some of the children were critically wounded and needed to lie on stretchers during the flight. The war, triggered by a Hamas attack in October.
articles.title: First planeload of wounded Palestinian children from Israel-Hamas arrives in United Arab Emirates

articles.description: A bottle of The Macallan 1926, considered the most valuable whisky in the world, was sold for a record 2.1 million euros at Sotheby's auction. This exceeded the estimated price range of 750,000 to 1.2 million euros. The sale set a new record for any bottle of spirit or wine sold at auction. The Macallan 1926 is a rare and highly sought-after whisky, with only 40 bottles verified by the distillery. It has been aged for 60 years and has a rich and complex flavor profile.
articles.title: 'Most valuable whisky' sold at record breaking price

articles.description: An Israeli drone targeted an aluminum plant in southern Lebanon, causing a fire and significant damage. There is no information yet on any casualties. This is the first strike in the area since the 2006 war between Israel and Hezbollah. Firefighters and ambulances have been dispatched to the scene, and journalists have been prevented from accessing the factory. The Israeli military has not yet commented on the strike, but they have stated that they are currently targeting Hezbollah.
articles.title: Israeli drone fires missiles at aluminum plant in south Lebanon

articles.description: Former Pakistani Prime Minister Shehbaz Sharif, along with two members of the federal caretaker cabinet, has been acquitted in a major housing corruption case. The Accountability Court Lahore judge acquitted Shehbaz, Fawad Hassan Fawad, Ahad Khan Cheema, and others based on a report from the national anti-graft body. The judge stated that there was no probability of conviction in the case. The Sharif brothers and other members of the Pakistan Muslim League-Nawaz (PML-N) party have been receiving relief from courts in various corruption cases since April 2022.
articles.title: Pakistan accountability court acquits former PM Shehbaz Sharif, others in corruption case

articles.description: Australia has accused the Chinese navy of causing minor injuries to Australian naval divers by operating sonar near their ship. The Australian government has expressed concerns to China over the unsafe conduct. The incident occurred while the Australian ship was clearing fishing nets from its propellers in international waters. Analysts fear that such actions could lead to a conflict. The incident comes after prime minister Anthony Albanese's visit to Beijing to improve relations.
articles.title: Australia says its navy divers were likely injured by the Chinese navy's 'unsafe' use of sonar

articles.description: Daisaku Ikeda, the former head of Soka Gakkai, a Japanese Buddhist organization, has died at the age of 95. He is credited with reviving Nichiren Buddhism and making it more accessible to modern practitioners. Soka Gakkai has millions of members worldwide, including famous musicians and celebrities. Ikeda emphasized the importance of happiness and spreading goodness in his teachings. He played a key role in spreading the teachings abroad and founded Soka Gakkai International. Ikeda's private funeral has already been held, and a public commemorative service will be announced later.
articles.title: Daisaku Ikeda, head of global Japanese Buddhist organization Soka Gakkai, dies at 95

articles.description: Hungarian prime Minister Viktor Orban has called for a change in the current European Union (EU) model built in Brussels, rather than completely abandoning it. Orban reiterated his opposition to starting talks with Ukraine about its EU membership, stating that Ukraine is far from meeting EU standards. He also expressed his resistance to the EU's strategy of settling migrants in Hungary. Orban's government has been at odds with Brussels over EU funds frozen due to democratic concerns.
articles.title: Hungary needs to change the EU, not leave it: PM Viktor Orban

articles.description: Over 80 people were killed in twin Israeli strikes on the Jabalia refugee camp in the Gaza Strip. One strike targeted a UN-run school, which had been converted into a shelter for displaced Palestinians, resulting in at least 50 deaths. The UN agency for Palestinian refugees condemned the attack, calling for an end to such violence. Another strike on a building in the camp killed 32 members of the same family, including 19 children. The Israeli army stated that it was expanding operations in the Gaza Strip to target terrorists and strike Hamas infrastructure.
articles.title: Hamas health ministry says more than 80 dead in strikes on refugee camp

articles.description: Iceland's Prime Minister, Katrin Jakobsdottir, has stated that no other country is better prepared for natural disasters than Iceland, as the nation braces for a potential volcanic eruption near the capital city, Reykjavik. The residents of Grindavik were evacuated after earthquakes indicated an impending eruption. The Reykjanes peninsula has experienced three eruptions in 2021, suggesting a new era of volcanic activity in the region. The government's priority is to support the affected residents by ensuring adequate salaries and finding suitable housing for them.
articles.title: Iceland PM says no country more prepared for volcano threat

Getty Images
    

  
How we turned 20,000 Soviet nukes into zero-carbon energy — and how we can do the same with some of our own.
 Just a decade ago, one in 10 American lightbulbs was powered by dismantled Russian nuclear weapons.
That was made possible by the Megatons to Megawatts program, an agreement negotiated after the collapse of the Soviet Union to convert uranium from Russia’s nuclear weapons stockpile into fuel for US nuclear power plants. The unconventional policy was first proposed by MIT physicist Thomas Neff in a 1991 New York Times op-ed. Fox Business host Maria Bartiromo, who infamously peddled conspiracy theories about the 2020 election that were concocted by a woman who believes she can talk with the wind, is now floating wild conspiracy theories about the origins of COVID-19.
While there is still some debate over whether COVID-19 may have originated from a viral research lab in the city of Wuhan, Bartiromo on Monday took things several steps farther — and suggested that the virus was part of a deliberate plot to bring down former President Donald Trump.
During an interview with Rep. Brad Wenstrup (R-OH), Bartiromo openly asked, "Is there a chance that China released this virus on America intentionally?"
In fact, there is no evidence of a Chinese plot to deliberately release a virus that spread all across the globe, not just in the United States, and that wound up killing millions of people, including an unquantified number of Chinese citizens.

articles.author: Agence France-Presse
articles.description:
At least 21 people, including three children, died after heavy rainfall inundated the Dominican Republic over the weekend, authorities said Sunday, warning the downpours were linked to worsening climate change.
Torrential storms over the past 48 hours have caused flooding, damaged infrastructure and brought down houses in the Caribbean nation, in what President Luis Abinader has called the "largest rainfall event ever" in the country's history.
"Those who do not believe in climate change, start believing," said Abinader, who spoke of "extensive and substantial" damages, though without detailing precise figures.
The rains, from a tropical depression, are expected to continue across portions of the country for the next 24 hours, the US embassy said in a weather alert.
In one particularly deadly incident, a wall collapsed Sunday onto several vehicles traveling on a major avenue in the capital, Santo Domingo, killing nine.
The water "infiltrated a saturated subsoil," and the foundation of the concrete wall gave way, the Ministry of Public Works said Sunday.
An investigation into the incident has been ordered by the ministry.
Nine other people died in separate instances in Santo Domingo on the same day. Others have died after being swept away by flood waters.
Some 13,000 people have been evacuated across the country, according to the Emergency Operations Center, and a majority of the nation's 32 provinces are under an alert designation.
(AFP)
articles.title: At least 21 dead after heavy rain causes flash flooding in Dominican Republic

articles.author: Sarah K. Burris
articles.description:
The man some called the Argentine Donald Trump has won Argentina's top post. 
Sunday evening, Javier Milei was declared the winner of the presidency in the country that has experienced significant inflation after the global pandemic. Despite this, Milei promised to kill government services, including healthcare, transportation and eliminate subsidies for utility bills, like gas, electricity and water. He intends to ban abortion and will refuse to take any action around climate change. 
In the past, the country has given funds to poor provinces in the country. Milei intends to cut those as well. 
The austerity measures are so significant that one NPR report suggested that the markets could crash in the country as a result of the election. After winning the primary, the country saw a slide, but not a crash. 
Donald Trump championed the win, posting on social media: "Congratulations to Javier Milei on a great race for President of Argentina. The whole world was watching! I am very proud of you. You will turn your Country around and truly Make Argentina Great Again!"
He followed it with a screen capture of a tweet showing the far-right libertarian standing behind a U.S. Gadsden flag.
articles.title: Far-right candidate Javier Milei wins Argentina election

IDF spokesperson Lieutenant Colonel Jonathan Conricus says the weapons found inside Al-Shifa Hospital prove Hamas uses hospitals for non-hospital purposes.

“We are going to prove by exposing the underground tunnels that we have started tapping into and by exploring the perimeter of the area and really getting into the deep underground of the hospital,” he told Sky News Australia.

“Then we will be able to prove that Hamas really uses this hospital as a command-and-control position.”

Lt Conricus forecasts the IDF will soon prove more as he claimed Hamas used the Al-Shifa Hospital on October 7 when they carried out terror attacks.

“We know the area is rife with Hamas operatives carrying weapons and patrolling the hospital.”

articles.description:
The 32 babies inside Al-Shifa Hospital in Gaza were safely evacuated to southern Gaza as the medical centre was captured without a single Palestinian being wounded, says IDF Spokesperson Lieutenant Colonel Jonathan Conricus.

“They were evacuated through incubators which we, the IDF, provided – I know so because I was on the ground,” he told Sky News Australia. 

Lt Conricus also denied reports babies died from lack of oxygen due to electricity supplies being turned off. 

“There was a convoy of Red Crescent ambulances that made its way through a humanitarian corridor that we facilitated from Shifa in northern Gaza towards southern Gaza.

“And the report that I have, which was confirmed also with the Egyptians, is they have arrived safely at the hospital in southern Gaza – all the babies that left the Shifa Hospital.”
articles.title: IDF’s Lt Conricus gives firsthand account of Al-Shifa babies’ safe evacuation

Reuters: Biggest protest in Spain against Catalan amnesty law draws 170000 
MADRID (Reuters) -About 170,000 people marched through Madrid on Saturday in the largest protest yet against an amnesty law which Spain's Socialists agreed over Catalonia's 2017 separatist bid in order to form a government. 
The demonstration, the latest in a series of protests in cities across the country against the amnesty, took place two days after Spain's Socialist Prime Minister Pedro Sanchez won a four-year term with the backing of Catalan and Basque nationalist parties in return for agreeing to the law. 
Protesters, many waving Spanish flags and holding signs that read "Sanchez traitor" and "Don't sell Spain", demonstrated against the law which four judicial associations, opposition political parties and business leaders said threatens the rule of law and the separation of powers.
